Body:
### Version

v3.0.6

### Platform

Linux

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Let's say I'm at `/home/ben/foo/`:
```ts
import * as path from "node:path";
import lume from "lume/mod.ts";

// "/home/ben/foo/../bar" = "/home/ben/bar"
const DESTINATION_DIRECTORY = path.resolve("../bar/");

console.log(DESTINATION_DIRECTORY); // "/home/ben/bar"

const site = lume({
  dest: DESTINATION_DIRECTORY,
});

export default site;
```

This results in the destination folder `/home/ben/foo/home/ben/bar`, instead of the expected `/home/ben/bar`.

Making use of relative paths works though:
```ts
import * as path from "node:path";
import lume from "lume/mod.ts";

const DESTINATION_DIRECTORY = path.resolve("../bar/");

const site = lume({
  dest: path.relative(Deno.cwd(), DESTINATION_DIRECTORY),
});

export default site;
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

Happens with an absolute `dest` site path.

### What is the expected behavior?

It should output the generated site at the absolute path.

### What do you see instead?

It outputs the absolute path relative to the current working directory.

### Additional information

_No response_

This affects to esbuild, highlightcss, etc.
Use: https://www.npmjs.com/package/baseline-browser-mapping

```js
import { getCompatibleVersions } from "npm:baseline-browser-mapping";

const results = getCompatibleVersions({
  widelyAvailableOnDate: "2025-06-21",
})
```

### Version

f57483a1d5db94ba956525471b96155cda5810fa

### Platform

macOS

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Setup highlightjs plugin, add placeholders to css in specific positions, see generated css, which just has the highlightjs css at the bottom of the file. 

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

Consistently

### What is the expected behavior?

I'd like to be able to specify the position of light and dark mode. 

Given: 

```ts
site.use(codeHighlight(
  {
    theme: [
      {
        name: "atom-one-light",
        cssFile: "styles.css",
        placeholder: "/* light-theme-here */"
      },
      {
        name: "atom-one-dark",
        cssFile: "styles.css",
        placeholder: "/* dark-theme-here */"
      },
    ],
    languages: {
      bash: lang_bash,
      css: lang_css,
      html: lang_html,
      json: lang_javascript_json,
      javascript: lang_javascript,
      typescript: lang_javascript_ts,
      js: lang_javascript,
      ts: lang_javascript_ts,
      powershell: lang_powershell,
      shell: lang_shell,
      sql: lang_sql,
      yaml: lang_yaml,
    },
  },
));
```

And in my styles.css:

```css
:root {
  ::selection {
    background-color: var(--color-sky-300);
    color: var(--color-zinc-900); 
  }

/* light-theme-here */

  .dark {
    ::selection {
      background-color: var(--color-sky-300);
      color: var(--color-zinc-900);
    }

/* dark-theme-here */

  }
}
```

If possible I would like the classes to be merged in position I specify, so they are picked up with the correct mode.


### What do you see instead?

The css classes are merged in, at the bottom of the styles.css file:

```css
...
hljs{padding:3px 5px}.hljs{color:#383a42;background:#fafafa}.hljs-comment,.hljs-quote{color:#a0a1a7;font-style:italic}.hljs-doctag,.hljs-formula,.hljs-keyword{color:#a626a4}.hljs-deletion,.hljs-name,.hljs-section,.hljs-selector-tag,.hljs-subst{color:#e45649}.hljs-literal{color:#0184bb}.hljs-addition,.hljs-attribute,.hljs-meta .hljs-string,.hljs-regexp,.hljs-string{color:#50a14f}.hljs-attr,.hljs-number,.hljs-selector-attr,.hljs-selector-class,.hljs-selector-pseudo,.hljs-template-variable,.hljs-type,.hljs-variable{color:#986801}.hljs-bullet,.hljs-link,.hljs-meta,.hljs-selector-id,.hljs-symbol,.hljs-title{color:#4078f2}.hljs-built_in,.hljs-class .hljs-title,.hljs-title.class_{color:#c18401}.hljs-emphasis{font-style:italic}.hljs-strong{font-weight:700}.hljs-link{text-decoration:underline}
pre code.hljs{display:block;overflow-x:auto;padding:1em}code.hljs{padding:3px 5px}.hljs{color:#abb2bf;background:#282c34}.hljs-comment,.hljs-quote{color:#5c6370;font-style:italic}.hljs-doctag,.hljs-formula,.hljs-keyword{color:#c678dd}.hljs-deletion,.hljs-name,.hljs-section,.hljs-selector-tag,.hljs-subst{color:#e06c75}.hljs-literal{color:#56b6c2}.hljs-addition,.hljs-attribute,.hljs-meta .hljs-string,.hljs-regexp,.hljs-string{color:#98c379}.hljs-attr,.hljs-number,.hljs-selector-attr,.hljs-selector-class,.hljs-selector-pseudo,.hljs-template-variable,.hljs-type,.hljs-variable{color:#d19a66}.hljs-bullet,.hljs-link,.hljs-meta,.hljs-selector-id,.hljs-symbol,.hljs-title{color:#61aeee}.hljs-built_in,.hljs-class .hljs-title,.hljs-title.class_{color:#e6c07b}.hljs-emphasis{font-style:italic}.hljs-strong{font-weight:700}.hljs-link{text-decoration:underline}
EOF
```

The dark mode happened to be second, so it takes precedence, and even in light mode, the dark mode is displayed on the generated page. 

### Additional information

_No response_

### Version

v2.5.2

### Platform

13.7.1

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

1. Setup the plugin with its defaults
2. `@import` a local CSS located in `_includes`

---

1. Same as above
2. `@import using the `npm:` scheme

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

In my testing, always. I tried both with a local CSS file as well as a CSS file using the `npm:` scheme.

### What is the expected behavior?

The plugin should minify the CSS (as per the plugin defaults) and also be able to resolve `@imports` either from the `includes` folder or via the `npm:scheme`.

I’m `@import`-ing the local file [relative](https://lightningcss.dev/bundling.html#%40import) to the `_includes` folder.

### What do you see instead?

No bundling. No minification.

<details><summary>Screenshot of browser console logs</summary>

<img width="569" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f0648fc1-6bb2-456f-afe8-bec6447991ec" />

</details> 

### Additional information

Here’s the relevant parts of my `_config.ts`:

```ts
// Trying to `@import` using the `npm:` scheme
import css from "lume/plugins/lightningcss.ts";

const site = lume({
  src: "./source",
  watcher: {
    debounce: 1_000,
  },
});

site
  .use(css())
// there’s more plugins, LightningCSS being the first one

site.copy("/styles.css");

export default site;
```

```css
/* Import when using the `npm:` scheme */
@import "npm:modern-normalize/modern-normalize.css";
```

---

```ts
// Trying to `@import` using a local file
import css from "lume/plugins/lightningcss.ts";

const site = lume({
  src: "./source",
  watcher: {
    debounce: 1_000,
  },
});

site
  .use(css())
// there’s more plugins, LightningCSS being the first one

site.copy("/styles.css");

export default site;
```

```css
/* Import when using a local file */
@import "./reset.css";
```

Output of `tree source`:

```sh
source
├── _includes
│   ├── article.vto
│   ├── layout.vto
│   ├── reset.css
├── server.ts
├── styles.css
```

**PS**: Maybe I’m not using the plugin correctly, in which case thanks for pointing me in the right direction!

### Version

2.5.0

### Platform

darwin

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Configure Lume to use TailwindCSS:

```ts
site.use(
    tailwindcss({
        options: {
            plugins: [typography],
        },
    }),
);
site.use(postcss());
```

Add tailwind directives and a local import to your CSS file:

```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

@import "assets/css/custom.css";
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

_No response_

### What is the expected behavior?

The custom CSS should be inlined.

### What do you see instead?

The custom CSS doesn't get inlined.

### Additional information

Doing the import first resolves the problem:

```css
@import "assets/css/custom.css";

@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

I wonder if it's a Lume or a TailwindCSS issue. I'm not sure to be honest. I could very well have missed something, but it's weird that moving the import to the top makes the issue go away.

### Enter your suggestions in details:

I'm considering to create a `Card` component that automatically displays the title and other information of given URL using OGP, like:

```tsx
import ogs from "open-graph-scraper"

interface CardData extends Lume.Data {
  href: string
}

export default async ({ href }: CardData) => {
  const { result } = await ogs({ // Result should be cached, omitting for now
    url: href,
  })

  return (
    <a href={href}>
      <div>{result.ogTitle}</div>
      <div>{result.ogDescription}</div>
    </a>
  )
}

// Can be used like: <comp.Card href="https://ogp.me" />
```

But it's not possible for now as async components are not supported.

Although it might be possible to fetch OGP data using `site.process`, I don't think it's an intuitive way. I would much appreciate if it's supported.

I have this config:
```ts
import lume from "lume/mod.ts";
import wiki from "wiki/mod.ts";
import esbuild from "lume/plugins/esbuild.ts";

const site = lume({
  src: "./docs",
});

site.use(esbuild({
  extensions: [".ts", ".js"],
  options: {
    plugins: [],
    bundle: true,
    format: "esm",
    minify: false,
    keepNames: true,
    platform: "browser",
    target: "esnext",
    entryPoints: ["./scripts/chart.ts"],
    outdir: "./",
    outbase: ".",
    charset: "utf8",
  },
}));
site.use(wiki());

export default site;
```
And this `index.md` in both `/` and `/docs`:
```md
---
extra_head: <script src="./scripts/chart.js" type="module"></script>
---
<div id="main" style="width: 100%; height: 500px"></div>
```
When `src: "./docs"` is commented, then the bundled scripts exist in `_site`. But when it is uncommented, there is no bundled script.

Lume v2.4.3

### Enter your suggestions in details:

In [`deno-docs`](https://github.com/denoland/deno-docs/) we have a good amount of pages both hand-written and generated ones.

I often find myself confused because the data for a page is scattered among numerous `export`s:

```
export const sectionTitle = "Lint rules";

export const layout = "lintRule.tsx";

export const toc = [];

export default function* (_data: Lume.Data, helpers: Lume.Helpers) {
  ...
}
```

I'd like to request (and I'm happy to work on it) to force using object notation for a page. So the above would become:

```ts
export default {
  sectionTitle: "Lint rules",
  layout: "lintRule.tsx",
  toc: [],
  component: function*(...) { // probably a wrong name
    ...
  }
}
```

It would be great if this could be forced in the `lume()` config like so:
```ts
import lume from "lume/mod.ts"

const site = lume(
  requirePageIsADefaultExport: true // open to bike shedding, effectively if it's specified throw an error if the default export is not an object containing all the configuration
  ...
);
```

### Version

2.4.3

### Platform

Windows

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

I want to use the pattern [encouraged by the official Deno docs](https://docs.deno.com/runtime/fundamentals/standard_library/#importing-standard-library-modules) of using specifiers like

```js
import { escape as htmlEscape } from "@std/html/entities";
```

and then in `deno.json` mapping `@std/html` to `jsr:@std/html@^1.0.3`.

However, when Lume with the esbuild plugin compiles these files, it accidentally inserts an extra slash: the output is

```js
import { escape as htmlEscape } from "https://esm.sh/jsr//@std/html@^1.0.3/entities";
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

Full repro:

**deno.json**

```json
{
  "imports": {
    "@std/html": "jsr:@std/html@^1.0.3",
    "lume/": "https://deno.land/x/lume@v2.4.2/"
  },
  "tasks": {
    "lume": "echo \"import 'lume/cli.ts'\" | deno run -A -",
    "build": "deno task lume",
    "serve": "deno task lume -s"
  },
  "compilerOptions": {
    "types": [
      "lume/types.ts"
    ]
  }
}
```

**_config.ts**

```ts
import lume from "lume/mod.ts";
import esbuild from "lume/plugins/esbuild.ts";

const site = lume({
  src: "./src",
});

site.copy([".html"]);

site.use(esbuild({
  extensions: [".ts"],
  options: {
    bundle: false,
    minify: false,
    treeShaking: false,
    keepNames: false,
  },
}));

export default site;
```

**src/index.html**
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<title>Test</title>

<script type="module" src="test.js"></script>
```

**src/test.ts**
```ts
import { escape as htmlEscape } from "@std/html/entities";

document.body.innerHTML = htmlEscape("Hello <from Lume>!");
```

### What is the expected behavior?

The output in `_site/test.js` should be something like

```js
import { escape as htmlEscape } from "https://esm.sh/jsr/@std/html@^1.0.3/entities";
document.body.innerHTML = htmlEscape("Hello <from Lume>!");
```

### What do you see instead?

The output in `_site/test.js` is instead

```js
import { escape as htmlEscape } from "https://esm.sh/jsr//@std/html@^1.0.3/entities";
document.body.innerHTML = htmlEscape("Hello <from Lume>!");
```

### Additional information

This is relatively important if one has code that is running both as part of the build process and in the built output.

### Version

2.3.0

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Install the ESbuild plugin & define outfile this way:

```js
import lume from "lume/mod.ts";
import esbuild from "lume/plugins/esbuild.ts";

const site = lume();

site.use(esbuild({
    options: {
        outfile: 'app.js'
    }
}))

export default site;

```

### What is the expected behavior?

Should use the outfile

### What do you see instead?

`[ERROR] Cannot use both "outfile" and "outdir"`.

### Additional information

Seems logic however because [the default ESbuild plugin configuration includes an `outdir`](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/blob/dbf547729a2f071ba2af90e69df74dc2d623042d/plugins/esbuild.ts#L63), but I don't think its possible to overwrite it. 

(Tried to pass it false or undefined but dind't work, its expecting a string)

### Enter your suggestions in details:

Lume by default doesn't allow to export two urls with the same name but different cases (like `/example/` and `/Example/`).

This restriction will be disabled with a new option:

```js
const site = lume({
  caseSensitiveUrls: true
});
```

### Version

2.2.2

### Platform

Linux

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Using the following `posts.page.ts` and `layout.vto`, generated items are not found by `search.pages()`. 

posts.page.ts:

```typescript
import Metalsmith from "npm:metalsmith";

export const layout = "layout.vto";
export const renderOrder = -1;

//this doesn't work ...
const sourcedir = '/path/to/other/dir/with/markdown-files';
const source = await Metalsmith('.')
  .source(sourcedir)
  .process();   //returns a promise
const articles = Object.values(source);

//but neither does this
const articles2 = [
  {
    title: 'foobar',
    publish: {
      slug: 'foobar'
    },
    contents: 'nothing to see here'
  },
  {
    title: 'barbaz',
    publish: {
      slug: 'barbaz'
    },
    contents: 'very interesting stuff here'
  }
]

export default function* () {
  //for (const article of articles) {
  for (const article of articles2) {
    yield {
      url: '/post/'+article.publish.slug,
      title: article.title,
      content: article.contents,
      type: "mytype"
    }
  }
}
```
template:

```html
<html lang="en">
<!--other stuff ...->

  <h2>Articles</h2>
{{for item of search.pages("url^=/post")}}
<p class="flex stretch | article-list"><a href="{{item.url}}">{{item.title}}</a></p>
{{/for}}

</body>
</html>
```


### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

_No response_

### What is the expected behavior?

posts should show up in search results.



### What do you see instead?

I think I've confirmed that it doesn't have to do with the async nature of the datasource by replacing that with a literal array -- same result. But I'm not sure ...

I also think it's not `renderOrder` (for example, #275 ) because I've inspected the pages in both `beforeRender` and `afterRender` events and the renderOrder is as I set it in my page files.

I do think it has to do with the generated nature of the pages, because if I modify the `search.pages()` query -- for example, to `!url^=/post` then I get all my items with a direct file origin.

The generated pages do get rendered and have urls starting with `/post`.

I can't tell the difference between my setup and the examples in the docs ... using top-level await or a literal array doesn't seem to make a difference.

### Additional information

I can't figure it out ... any ideas?

### Version

any

### Platform

any

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

enable jsx_preact and inline.
The preact types doesn't include the `inline` attribute types so it shows a warning in vscode.

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

always

### What is the expected behavior?

do not fail

### What do you see instead?

![imaxe](https://github.com/lumeland/lume/assets/377873/d6348278-df07-4485-a85a-26ea42330928)


### Additional information

A solution:

```ts
// types.d.ts
declare global {
  namespace preact.JSX {
    interface HTMLAttributes {
      inline?: boolean | undefined;
    }
  }
}
```

### Version

v2.2

### Platform

Win10

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

我根据官方的 [Simple Blog](https://lume.land/theme/simple-blog/) 模板，简化写了一个类似的`Theme`插件，部署在[deno.land/x](https://deno.land/x/lume_theme_blog)，如果我的 `markdown file`  放在本地磁盘，它会工作良好，但是如果我的数据是放在`supabase`，比如：

```typescript
import { Orm } from "jsr:@xtool/mod";

const db = new Orm({
  user: Deno.env.get("SUPABASE_USER"),
  password: Deno.env.get("SUPABASE_PASSWORD"),
  hostname: Deno.env.get("SUPABASE_HOSTNAME"),
  CERT: Deno.env.get("SUPABASE_CERT"),
});

const res = await db.select().table("posts");
export default function* () {
  for (const article of res.rows) {
    article.date = article.created_at;  // Lume default use date property
    yield {
      type: "post",
      layout: "post.vto",
      origin: "supabase",
      url: `/posts/${article.title}/`,
      ...article
    };
  }
}
```

动态生成的页面，那么 `Theme` 中的 `archive.page.js` 中， `search.pages("", "date=desc")` 中返回为0.

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

every time

### What is the expected behavior?

 `xxx.page.js` 应该控制一下调用的顺序，防止 `pages` 没有正确装载。

### What do you see instead?

output 0

### Additional information

nothing

### Version

2.2

### Platform

win / lin amd

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

if src is set, static doesn't copy. in this configuration everything works fine. as soon as I uncomment src: "docs", none of those copy commands work.
```js
// _config.ts
const site = lume({
    // src: "docs",
});

site.copy("./static", ".");
site.copy("../static", ".");
site.copy("static", ".");
site.copy("static");
```

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

always

### What is the expected behavior?

static files should copy even if I set src.

### What do you see instead?

no copy unless src left at default

### Additional information

i spend several hours trying to nail it down, and as far as I can tell copy just doesn't do anything when src is set. I tried many combinations of paths (the docs say static should be relative to docs, and I tried that as well). I tried all different names to make sure there was no magic name handling (i started with _static) but nothing seemed to make a difference. If src is set, copy doesn't work in any combination I came up with.

### Version

2.1.3

### Platform

macOS

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

Let's say I have a bunch of [`.cook` files](https://cooklang.org/docs/) in a `recipes` folder. I'd like to render these as HTML with a layout, but *also* serve these raw `.cook` files in the built site.

It's the same scenario as wanting to keep the source `.md` files in a blog and serve along side built `.html` files, or keep raw `.json` files and serve as a JSON API.

I have a hard time finding my way around the docs to find an _elegant_ solution for this.

**What I landed on now:**

```ts
// _config.ts
import { copy, expandGlob } from 'std/fs/mod.ts';

const SRC =  'src';
const DEST = 'build';

const site = lume({
    src: SRC,
    dest: DEST,
});

site
    .data('layout', 'layouts/reci.njk', '/recipes')
     // Makes src/recipes/*.cook → build/recipes/*/index.html
    .loadPages(['.cook'], async (path) => {
        const text = await Deno.readTextFile(path);
        return parseToRecipe(text); // irrelevant
    })
    // Makes src/recipes/*.cook → build/recipes/*.cook
    .addEventListener('afterBuild', async () => {
        // Fiddly, since we don't want to overwrite the existing build/recipes directory from above
        for await (const entry of expandGlob(`./src/recipes/*.cook`)) {
            await copy(entry.path, `./${DEST}/recipes/${entry.name}`);
        }
    })
```

I've tried various combinations of:

* `Site.copy()`: this would overwrite the built `build/recipes` dir.
* `Site.loadAssets()`.
* `Site.loadData()`.

I've read https://lume.land/docs/core/loaders top to bottom. The key paragraph for my issue is:

> Note: you can't use the same extension to generate pages and assets, so a way to have support for both is adding a sub-extension (like .page) for pages

***

**Is my solution above the best one so far?**

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

_No response_

### What is the expected behavior?

_No response_

### What do you see instead?

-

### Additional information

Related as input to:

* https://github.com/lumeland/lume/issues/571
* https://github.com/lumeland/lume/issues/428

### Enter your suggestions in details:

To allow the on-demand generation of pages based on an async operation (like a fetch from an external source) the `extraData` function should allow Promises or async.

When I try this I get an internal server error:

```
site.use(onDemand({
  extraData(request: Request) {
    const searchParams = new URL(request.url).searchParams;
    const params = Object.fromEntries(searchParams.entries());

    return new Promise ((resolve, reject)=>{
      setTimeout(()=>{
        resolve({params})
      },1000)
    })
  },
}));
```

marking the function as `async` also gives an error.

I think an `await` in this line https://github1s.com/lumeland/lume/blob/main/middlewares/on_demand.ts#L42-L43
could do the trick to allow for async `extraData` functions.

### Version

- Deno@1.36.4 
- lume@v1.18.5

### Platform

Windows

### What steps will reproduce the bug?

When using plain ES modules (.tmpl.ts) as templates, reloading in the browser does not work for imported sub-templates.

e.g. 

```ts
// default.tmpl.ts

import { PageData } from "lume/core.ts";
import headTmpl from "../_components/head.tmpl.ts";
import bodyTmpl from "../_components/body.tmpl.ts";

export default (data: PageData) => {
  return /*html*/ `<html>
  ${headTmpl(data)}
  <body>
    ${bodyTmpl(data)}
  </body>
</html>`;
};

```

May related to: https://github.com/lumeland/lume/issues/178

### How often does it reproduce? Is there a required condition?

_No response_

### What is the expected behavior?

_No response_

### What do you see instead?

No changes will be shown if anything is changed in a subtemplate.

### Additional information

A current workaround might be to define all subtemplates in the same file. However, this prevents reuse in some situations.

e.g. 

```ts
// default.tmpl.ts
import { PageData } from "lume/core.ts";

const bodyTmpl = (data: PageData) => {
  return /*html*/ `<div>
    ${data.content}
   </div>`;
};

const headTmpl = (data: PageData) => {
  return /*html*/ `<head>
  <title>${data.title}</title>
  ...
</head>`;
};

export default (data: PageData) => {
  return /*html*/ `<html>
  ${headTmpl(data)}
  <body>
    ${bodyTmpl(data)}
  </body>
</html>`;
